body:
Does the [ONNX checker](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/PythonAPIOverview.md#checking-an-onnx-model) consider the model valid?
If not then this is likely a bug in the sklearn-onnx converter and you should file it there: https://github.com/onnx/sklearn-onnx

If yes, then this is either a bug in ONNX Runtime, or the ONNX checker needs to become more strict.
The model checks out as valid from the "onnx_checker" snippet on the provided link.

ONNX checker may have a gap.

The spec for [DictVectorizer](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators-ml.md#aionnxmldictvectorizer) says map(string,bool) is supported but your model seems to have `map(string,tensor(bool))`

I don't know why the model is generated with tensor(bool) instead of bool for the value. @xadupre may be able to help with that. Wild guess would be to try StringType for key with BooleanType for value.

I checked [this](https://github.com/onnx/sklearn-onnx/blob/master/skl2onnx/common/data_types.py) link. There is `BooleanTensorType` but I could not see `BooleanType`. 

By the way the type constraints for [DictVectorizer](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators-ml.md#aionnxmldictvectorizer) are stated as

`T1 : map(string, int64), map(int64, string), map(int64, float), map(int64, double), map(string, float), map(string, double)`

I could not see `map(string, bool)`

I created a PR to investigate: https://github.com/onnx/sklearn-onnx/pull/805. It works if you replace the BooleanTensorType with FloatTensorType. It should not impact your performance. onnxruntime only supports float values and int64, string keys. See https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/onnxruntime_pybind_mlvalue.cc#L648.
@dafajon if you'd be so generous, please file an issue in onnx/onnx about the ONNX checker not failing. If you can upload the .onnx file that would be helpful.

@garymm Thank you I am on it.
@xadupre Thank you I am going to try that way. I will let you know if there are any issues.

issue.title: ONNX Checker does not fail for DictVectorizer saved with unsupported input types

repository.name: onnx
repository.description: Open standard for machine learning interoperability

issue.body:
### Bug Report
I previously had a conversion [issue](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/10098) with onnx runtime for a model successfully dumped with `skl2onnx`.

Even though there is no support for `map(stringTensor, booleanTensor)`  and `map(string, booleanTensor)` in the [spec](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators-ml.md#aionnxmldictvectorizer) for `DictVectorizer`, the ONNX Checker does not fail for the serialized model with above input types. 

System info, code for the case and the model file are provided below.

### System information
- OS Platform and Distribution: MacOS 10.14.2
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): PyPI 1.10.0
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.10.0
- Python version: 3.8.12
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): None
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): None
- CUDA/cuDNN version: None
- GPU model and memory: None


### Reproduction instructions
```python
mdl = onnx.load_model("sbd.onnx")

try:
  onnx.checker.check_model(mdl)
except onnx.checker.ValidationError as e:
  print('The model is invalid: %s' % e)


else:
  print('The model is valid!') 
```
### Model file

[sbd.onnx.zip](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/files/7780842/sbd.onnx.zip)

### Expected behavior
```ValidationError("The model is invalid.")```

body:
I have completed my work with the `onnx` model by using your suggested workaround. You can close this issue if that is all. Will there be any support of `BooleanTensorType` in the future? 

Best.

> Will there be any support of `BooleanTensorType` in the future?

That would require an update to the ONNX spec for the operator. If you can make a case that the implementation cost of adding support for bool provides enough benefit please request any spec update via https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues. As the existing supported types can be used to represent a bool the benefit seems limited to me.
Seems the issue is resolved, so closing. Please comment if I'm mistaken.
